ğŸ”¸ What is a Pointer in C?
  ğŸ‘‰A pointer is a variable that stores the memory address of another variable.
  ğŸ‘‰It is a powerful feature that provides flexibility and direct memory access.

int a = 10;
int *p = &a;   // p stores address of variable 'a'



ğŸ”¸ Declaration of Pointer
  datatype *pointer_name;
âœ… Example:
int *ptr;    // pointer to int  
float *fptr; // pointer to float



ğŸ”¸ Initialization of Pointer
int a = 5;
int *ptr = &a;  // ptr holds address of a




ğŸ”¸ Dereferencing a Pointer
  ğŸ‘‰Accessing value at the address stored by the pointer using * operator.
printf("%d", *ptr);  // prints value of a, i.e., 5


ğŸ”¸ Size of Pointer
  ğŸ‘‰The size of a pointer depends on the system architecture (e.g., 4 bytes on 32-bit, 8 bytes on 64-bit systems).
int *ptr;
printf("%lu", sizeof(ptr));  // Output depends on system




ğŸ”¸ Special Types of Pointers
  ğŸ‘‰NULL Pointer
      int *ptr = NULL;   // pointer points to nothing

  ğŸ‘‰Void Pointer
      void *ptr;   // generic pointer, can point to any data type

  ğŸ‘‰Wild Pointer
     int *ptr;   // uninitialized pointer, dangerous!

  ğŸ‘‰Dangling Pointer
     Points to memory that is freed or out of scope.

ğŸ”¸ Pointer Arithmetic
  ğŸ‘‰Allowed operations:
  ğŸ‘‰Increment: ptr++
  ğŸ‘‰Decrement: ptr--
  ğŸ‘‰Addition/Subtraction: ptr + n, ptr - n

âœ… Example:
int arr[] = {10, 20, 30};
int *p = arr;
printf("%d", *(p + 1));  // 20


ğŸ”¸ Constant Pointers
  ğŸ‘‰Pointer to Constant
const int *ptr;  // data is constant, pointer can change

  ğŸ‘‰Constant Pointer
int *const ptr;  // pointer is constant, data can change

  ğŸ‘‰Constant Pointer to Constant
const int *const ptr;  // both pointer and data are constant


ğŸ”¸ Pointer to Function
  ğŸ‘‰A pointer storing address of a function.

âœ… Syntax:
return_type (*ptr)(parameter_list);

âœ… Example:
int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
int (*fptr)(int, int) = add;
printf("%d", fptr(3, 4));  // Output: 7


ğŸ”¸ Multilevel Pointers (Pointer to Pointer)
âœ… Declaration:
int **pp;

âœ… Example:
int a = 10;
int *p = &a;
int **pp = &p;
printf("%d", **pp);   // Output: 10
